<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="462" pageId="10" pageNumber="461" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,1941,2038]" lastBlockId="11.[151,1436,151,464]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="462" pageId="10" pageNumber="461">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1941,1966]" pageId="10" pageNumber="461">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[564,739,1942,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transpositum">
<emphasis box="[564,579,1942,1965]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="461">L</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[593,739,1942,1965]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="461">transpositum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from eastern Asia. It is separated from 
<taxonomicName box="[1184,1359,1942,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transpositum">
<emphasis box="[1184,1359,1942,1965]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="461">L. transpositum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the following character states: female supraclypeus with sparser PP (IS = 3 d in maximum); female labrum with small lateral projection on distal process (
<bibRefCitation author="Murao" box="[552,949,2013,2038]" pageId="10" pageNumber="461" refString="Murao, R. &amp; Tadauchi, O. (2008 b) Taxonomic notes and floral associations of Lasioglossum (Evylaeus) transpositum and L. (E.) metis (Hymenoptera, Halictidae). Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 14 (1), 95 - 106." type="journal article" year="2008" yearSuffix="b">
Murao &amp; Tadauchi 2008b, 
<figureCitation box="[860,925,2013,2038]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1655,1677]" captionTargetBox="[151,1419,195,1628]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1435,195,1634]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 3. A: pronotum in lateral view. B, C: posterior surface of propodeum. D, E: posterior area of mesoscutum. A: Lasioglossum apristum (Vachal). B: L. affine (Smith). C: L. transpositum (Cockerell). D: L. sibiriacum (Blüthgen). E: L. hoffmanni (Strand). A – E: ♀." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/580874/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="461">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
G
</bibRefCitation>
); female postgena with distinct lineolation; mesepisternum nearly smooth on upper area in both sexes; and male metasomal sterna with uniform and sparse hairs. In contrast, in 
<taxonomicName box="[380,556,189,212]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transpositum">
<emphasis box="[380,556,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">L. transpositum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, female supraclypeus with denser PP (IS = 1.5 d in maximum), female labrum without lateral projection on distal process (
<bibRefCitation author="Murao" box="[651,1052,223,248]" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" refString="Murao, R. &amp; Tadauchi, O. (2008 b) Taxonomic notes and floral associations of Lasioglossum (Evylaeus) transpositum and L. (E.) metis (Hymenoptera, Halictidae). Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 14 (1), 95 - 106." type="journal article" year="2008" yearSuffix="b">
Murao &amp; Tadauchi 2008b, 
<figureCitation box="[963,1027,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1717,1739]" captionTargetBox="[151,1419,257,1689]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1435,257,1695]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. A: fore wing of female. B – E: lateral habitus of four subgenera of Lasioglossum occurring in South Korea. A – B: L. (Acanthalictus) dybowskii (Radoszkowski). C: L. (Dialictus) miyabei Murao, Ebmer &amp; Tadauchi. D: L. (Hemihalictus) transpositum (Cockerell). E: L. (Sphecodogastra) apristum (Vachal). A – E: ♀." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/580872/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
H
</bibRefCitation>
), female postgena nearly smooth, mesepisternum punctate on upper area in both sexes, and male S2–S5 lateroapically with thin hair tufts (
<bibRefCitation author="Murao" pageId="11" pageNumber="462" refString="Murao, R. &amp; Tadauchi, O. (2008 b) Taxonomic notes and floral associations of Lasioglossum (Evylaeus) transpositum and L. (E.) metis (Hymenoptera, Halictidae). Japanese Journal of Systematic Entomology, 14 (1), 95 - 106." type="journal article" year="2008" yearSuffix="b">
Murao &amp; Tadauchi 2008b, 
<figureCitation box="[344,410,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1671,1693]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,195,1649]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[150,1436,195,1649]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. A, B: body color of head and mesosoma. C, D, F: mesepisternum. E: pronotum in lateral view. A: Lasioglossum ellipticeps (Blüthgen). B: L. calceatum (Scopoli). C: L. apristum (Vachal). D: L. miyabei Murao, Ebmer &amp; Tadauchi. E, F: L. percrassiceps (Cockerell). A – F: ♀." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/580873/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="462">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
F
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
